Phase 1-B: Client Fetch Timeout for Gemini
What: Add AbortSignal.timeout() to callViaProxy and callDirect in geminiClient.ts.
TDD sequence:
RED: Write test src/features/knowledgeBank/services/__tests__/geminiClient.timeout.test.ts:
Mock fetch to never resolve.
Assert callGemini(body) resolves within CLIENT_TIMEOUT_MS + buffer with { ok: false, status: 0, data: null }.
Assert that AbortSignal is passed to fetch.
GREEN: In geminiClient.ts:
Add export const CLIENT_TIMEOUT_MS = 35_000; — 5s above the server-side GEMINI_FETCH_TIMEOUT_MS (30s) in functions/src/utils/securityConstants.ts. The Cloud Function execution limit is 60s (default, no explicit config), but its internal fetch to Gemini aborts at 30s, so the function will respond within ~30s + overhead. Add a comment: `// Must exceed GEMINI_FETCH_TIMEOUT_MS (30s) in functions/src/utils/securityConstants.ts`
Add signal: AbortSignal.timeout(CLIENT_TIMEOUT_MS) to both fetch() calls in callViaProxy and callDirect.
The existing catch block in callGemini already returns { ok: false, status: 0, data: null } on any error, so the abort is handled.
REFACTOR: Extract the timeout constant to a named export for testability. No file size change (adds ~3 lines).
Build gate: npm run lint && npm run test && npm run build.
Tech debt incurred: None. The timeout is a constant, not hardcoded inline. The abort error flows through existing error handling. No new Zustand subscriptions, no useEffect changes.
Phase 1-C: Calendar Token Write Validation
What: Validate access_token format before storing in localStorage in connectGoogleCalendar.
TDD sequence:
RED: Write test src/features/auth/services/__tests__/calendarAuthService.validation.test.ts:
Mock GIS to return a token containing <script> or &;| — assert localStorage is NOT called, function returns false.
Mock GIS to return a valid base64 token (containing /, +, =) — assert localStorage.setItem is called.
GREEN: In calendarAuthService.ts, before lines 99-100:
Add: if (DANGEROUS_TOKEN_CHARS.test(token)) { resolve(false); return; }
Uses a blocklist regex instead of an allowlist — Google OAuth tokens are base64-encoded and may contain /, +, = which a narrow allowlist would reject. The blocklist targets XSS/injection chars only.
REFACTOR: Extract const DANGEROUS_TOKEN_CHARS = /[<>"'`;&|]/; to the top of the file. Use it in both getCalendarToken and connectGoogleCalendar (replacing the existing allowlist regex in getCalendarToken). File stays well under 200 lines.
Build gate: npm run lint && npm run test && npm run build.
Tech debt incurred: None. Blocklist regex is DRY (single constant). Validation is defense-in-depth alongside existing read-side check. Blocklist approach is resilient to OAuth token format changes.
